	<div class="cell large-12 small-12 main-content-well">
		<div class="story-content">
							<div class="story-info">
			<div class="featured-img-container">
			<img class="story-img" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/twitterbracketheaderday4.jpg" title="What Was Literary Twitter? The Bracket *Day 4*">
								</div>
		<div class="story-heads">
		<h1>What Was Literary Twitter? The Bracket *Day 4*</h1>
		<h2>The friends we made along the way</h2>	</div>
	</div>
										<div class="byline-date">
					<span class="byline"><a href="https://lithub.com/author/literary-hub/"  title="Literary Hub">Literary Hub</a></span>
					<span class="hr"></span>
					<span class="date">November 20, 2025</span>
				</div>
						<div class="story-body">
								<p>It’s day four, and only 8 out of original 64 are left after <a href="https://lithub.com/what-was-literary-twitter-the-bracket-day-3/">yesterday&#8217;s voting!</a> The polls today will determine who wins their quadrant (or is it “region”? Or “zone”? We’re not sports people) and advances to the semifinals.</p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><!-- Code from Primis: LitHub_static_to_float -->
<!-- Do not serve inside a SafeFrame -->
<script type="text/javascript" language="javascript" src="https://live.primis.tech/live/liveView.php?s=120997&schain=1.0,1!publift.com,01K5AHM87E14YH1C83WXZ8HCHJ,1&cbuster=%%CACHEBUSTER%%"></script>
<!-- End of code from Primis --></div>
<p>It’s starting to get down to the wire, with some very big Twitter moments getting eliminated yesterday. It was a bad day for bad men—the <b>shitty media men list</b> and the <b>men don’t read</b> discourse both lost—and big debates—<b>the literary world leaving Twitter</b> and <b>should adults read YA?</b> both got 86ed.</p>
<p>The Bret Easton Ellis <b>“come over at do bring coke now”</b> party Tweet was knocked out by <b>bad art friend.</b> Fitting for the day after the National Book Awards when we’re all a little sleepy and a few people could probably use a new kidney.</p>
<p>But today, you have four big match-ups to vote on. I&#8217;ll be watching the returns on the meme match-up, if you will, between <b>William Carlos Williams’ “This Is Just To Say” poem</b> and the satirical Twitter persona <b>@GuyInYourMFA.</b> I can definitely imagine MFA Guy being very salty in a workshop about what the Williams poem has become, while secretly sending a lot of plum parody poems in DMs.</p>
<p>And <b>Joyce Carol Oates</b> vs. <b>bad art friend</b> is a big face-off with finals level energy. I’m favoring JCO since she’s dominated every match-up so far, but who knows what could happen.</p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><!-- GAM 22020028882/LTHB_lithubcom/Article_Incontent_1 -->
<div data-fuse="Article_Incontent_1"></div></div>
<p>Readers, it’s up to you! The polls are open!</p>
<h3 style="text-align: center;">Behold, the updated Bracket:</h3>
<p><a href="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/twitterbracketday4-scaled.jpg"><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="263156" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/what-was-literary-twitter-the-bracket-day-4/twitterbracketday4/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/twitterbracketday4-scaled.jpg" data-orig-size="1587,2560" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="twitterbracketday4" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/twitterbracketday4-186x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/twitterbracketday4-635x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-263156" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/twitterbracketday4-scaled.jpg" alt="" width="1587" height="2560" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/twitterbracketday4-scaled.jpg 1587w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/twitterbracketday4-186x300.jpg 186w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/twitterbracketday4-635x1024.jpg 635w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/twitterbracketday4-768x1239.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/twitterbracketday4-37x60.jpg 37w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/twitterbracketday4-952x1536.jpg 952w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/twitterbracketday4-1270x2048.jpg 1270w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/twitterbracketday4-31x50.jpg 31w" sizes="(max-width: 1587px) 100vw, 1587px" /></a></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>[Click to enlarge]</em></p>
<h1 style="text-align: center;">*</h1>
<h3 style="text-align: center;">Rules</h3>
<p>Now that Literary Twitter is dead, we’re asking, “What was it?” In this bracket, we&#8217;re seeking the Most Literary Twitter moment, discourse, or personage. What has been stuck in your mind, who sent you running to your group chat, what kept you scrolling for longer than you should have? What are you still bringing up in conversation today and having to explain to people with normal brains? In short, what most exemplified whatever the hell Literary Twitter was?</p>
<p>We&#8217;ve sorted all of the contenders (that we can remember) into four categories: Existential Crises, Matters of Taste, Bad Behavior, and Reading Comprehension. Each quadrant&#8217;s winner will face off on Friday, before the final head-to-head on Monday, November 24th to crown our winner.</p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><!-- GAM 22020028882/LTHB_lithubcom/Article_Incontent_2 -->
<div data-fuse="Article_Incontent_2"></div></div>
<h1 style="text-align: center;">*</h1>
<h3 style="text-align: center;">Voting Schedule</h3>
<p><del><strong>Round of 64 Character Limit:</strong> Voting open now until tonight at 7:00 PM EST</del> <a href="https://lithub.com/what-was-literary-twitter-the-bracketwhat-was-literary-twitter-the-bracket/">(Check out the results from the first round here)</a></p>
<p><del><strong>Round of &#8220;dang, only 32 likes?&#8221;:</strong> Voting open Tuesday, November 18th from 10:00 AM – 7:00 PM EST</del><a href="https://lithub.com/what-was-literary-twitter-the-bracket-day-2/"> (Round two results are here</a>)</p>
<p><del><strong>Round of &#8220;sweet, 16 new followers&#8221;:</strong> Voting open Wednesday, November 19th from 10:00 AM – 7:00 PM EST</del> <a href="https://lithub.com/what-was-literary-twitter-the-bracket-day-3/">(Results from this round, here)</a></p>
<p><strong><em>You are here &#8211;&gt;</em> The Retweeted 8:</strong> Voting open Thursday, November 20th from 10:00 AM – 7:00 PM EST</p>
<p><strong>The Quarter Finals:</strong> Voting open Friday, November 21st from 10:00 AM, until Sunday November 23rd at 7:00 PM EST</p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><!-- GAM 22020028882/LTHB_lithubcom/Article_Incontent_3 -->
<div data-fuse="Article_Incontent_3"></div></div>
